<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation">
    <Paragraph FontSize="20">Command</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph LineHeight="2">
        <Run>A command is an imperative message that sounds like an explicit request made to the system to have some tasks performed. Here are some other characteristics of a command:</Run>
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Box" Margin="0 10 0 0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>A command is directed at one handler.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>A command can be rejected by the system.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>A command can fail while being executed by some handler.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>The net effect of the command can be different depending on the current state of the system.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>A command doesn’t generally trespass the boundaries of a given bounded context.</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph LineHeight="1" Margin="0 20 0 10">
        <TextBlock FontWeight="Bold">Tasks</TextBlock>
    </Paragraph>
    <List>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Add any input, validation or business rules
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Add a command return type if any (i.e. Command<![CDATA[<]]> Guid<![CDATA[>]]>)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
